        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(mxc): add Windows MXC sandbox backend",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nOpenClaw does not currently have a bundled MXC sandbox backend for Windows hosts that can run sandboxed commands through Microsoft eXecution Containers. This leaves MXC-capable Windows environments without a first-party plugin path for ProcessContainer-backed execution and filesystem bridge operations.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nThis adds a bundled `mxc` plugin with Windows-only readiness checks, plugin-local MXC SDK dependency ownership, ProcessContainer payload construction, a plugin-side launcher, host-backed filesystem bridge support, sandbox policy loading, and targeted tests. The implementation keeps core runtime changes out of the branch, keeps the backend dormant unless Windows MXC prerequisites are available, and hardens the sandbox boundary by using curated environments, headless UI defaults, per-exec temp directories, absolute binary overrides, host-derived Windows roots, and fail-closed unsupported policy handling.\n\n## User Impact\n\nUsers on MXC-capable Windows hosts can configure the bundled MXC plugin as a sandbox backend and run OpenClaw sandboxed commands through MXC. Non-Windows or unsupported Windows hosts remain unaffected because the plugin stays dormant when readiness probes fail.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- `pnpm test:extension mxc -- --reporter=verbose` — passed, 10 files / 88 tests.\n- `pnpm test extensions\\mxc -- --reporter=verbose` — passed, 10 files / 88 tests.\n- `pnpm test:changed` — passed, MXC extension shard.\n- `pnpm check` — passed, including import cycle check with 0 runtime value cycles.\n- `pnpm build` — passed.\n- `python .agents\\skills\\autoreview\\scripts\\autoreview --engine copilot --mode branch --base origin/main` — clean; no accepted/actionable findings; overall patch is correct (0.74).\n\nFull `pnpm test` was attempted per CONTRIBUTING, but the broad local suite hit unrelated existing non-MXC failures in UI/TUI/agent runtime tests before completion. The changed/MXC-specific lanes above passed cleanly.\n\n## Notes\n\n- Contributor changelog edit was removed per CONTRIBUTING.\n- `.github/labeler.yml` now maps `extensions/mxc/**` to `plugin: mxc`.\n- Upstream label verification found no existing `plugin: mxc` label; label creation was intentionally not performed.\r\n",
